SIMPLE: extreme
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Extreme
<hw>Ex*treme"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>extremus</ets>, superl. of <ets>exter</ets>, <ets>extrus</ets>, on
the outside, outward: cf. F. <ets>extr⟦ecir⟧me</ets>. See
<er>Exterior</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>At the utmost point, edge, or
border; outermost; utmost; farthest; most remote; at the widest
limit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Last; final; conclusive; -- said of time; <as>as,
the <ex>extreme</ex> hour of life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The best of worst; most urgent; greatest; highest;
immoderate; excessive; most violent; <as>as, an <ex>extreme</ex> case;
<ex>extreme</ex> folly.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>extremest</xex>
remedy.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dryden.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Extreme</xex>
rapidity.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir W. Scott.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet <qex>extreme</qex> gusts will blow out fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Radical; ultra; <as>as, <ex>extreme</ex>
opinions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Puritans or <qex>extreme</qex> Protestants.</q>
<rj><qau>Gladstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Extended or contracted as much as
possible; -- said of intervals; <as>as, an <ex>extreme</ex> sharp
second; an <ex>extreme</ex> flat forth.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Extreme and mean ratio</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>,
<cd>the relation of a line and its segments when the line is so divided
that the whole is to the greater segment is to the less.</cd> --
<col><b>Extreme distance</b></col>. <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Distance</er>., <pos>n.</pos>, 6.</cd> -- <col><b>Extreme
unction</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Unction</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Although this adjective, being superlative in
signification, is not properly subject to comparison, the superlative
form not unfrequently occurs, especially in the older writers.
⟦ldquo⟧Tried in his <xex>extremest</xex> state.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Spenser.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Extremest</xex> hardships.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sharp.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Extremest</xex> of evils.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Bacon.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Extremest</xex> verge of the swift brook.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧The sea's <xex>extremest</xex> borders.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Addison.</au></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extreme</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Extreme
<hw>Ex*treme"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The utmost point or
verge; that part which terminates a body; extremity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Utmost limit or degree that is supposable or
tolerable; hence, furthest degree; any undue departure from the mean; --
often in the plural: things at an extreme distance from each other, the
most widely different states, etc.; <as>as, <ex>extremes</ex> of heat
and cold, of virtue and vice; <ex>extremes</ex> meet.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His parsimony went to the <qex>extreme</qex> of meanness.</q>
<rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An extreme state or condition; hence, calamity,
danger, distress, etc.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Resolute in most
<xex>extremes</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>Either of the extreme terms of a
syllogism, the middle term being interposed between them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The first or the last term of a
proportion or series.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In the extreme</b></col> <cd>as much as possible.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧The position of the Port was difficult <xex>in the
extreme</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>J. P. Peters.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extremeless</ent>⟦br⟧
